Camille Auer wanted to correct her sex, diagnosed as mentally ill, and now she is making art on the subject - "Man should have the right to his own body"
There are dozens of patient reports hanging from the roof of the Art Academy’s Project room.
Each of them says the name of Camille Auer.
The papers tell a multi-faceted story of how outsiders have written down their interpretation of Auer and his identity.
Determined for him who he is.
I wanted to share my personal treatment history to make the violence of the process visible," Auer says.
In the process, he refers to the sex correction process.
It is often a years-long period of research involving meetings with psychologists, psychiatrists, nurses and doctors.
The process starts with a referral to the "gender identity disorder" -diagnosis studies that are being carried out in Tampere and Helsinki.
For Auer, the process started four years ago.
Even before this, he had used the estrogen he had ordered via the Internet and was already very long in his own repair process.
She felt like a woman, but according to Finnish law, a person must go through the repair process so that the sex can also be corrected legally.
The Trans-Law, i.e. the Act on the Strengthening of Transgender Sex (563/2002), obliges transgender people to undergo forced sterilisation in order to obtain the right gender, for example, in the Population Register Centre and in the passport.
At the moment, every correctionist of his gender is required to have a psychiatric diagnosis and evidence of reproductive inability.
Man has the right to decide about his own body.
This situation is intolerable and violates human rights," Auer said.
Translating has been discussed in Finland for a long time.
The UN Human Rights Council has issued eight observations on the law, and the European Court of Human Rights has a preliminary ruling that obliges the parties to the European Convention on Human Rights to respect the right to self-determination.
The previous Finnish Government prepared an amendment to the Act under the leadership of the then Minister of Social Affairs and Health, Susanne Huovinen.
Elections came and the Finns Party rose to the board.
Now the change in the law is back.
These are domestic disputes that do not even relate to this law.
The government does not want to put it on the table because there are disagreements within the government about changing the law," says Frank Johansson, Executive Director of Amnesty Finland.
The front of the exhibition space is dominated by two large installations.
One of them consists of the packaging and instructions for use of the medicines used by Auer.
In the patient report installation, any visitor can read, for example, the interpretation of the psychologist of the Tampere University Hospital’s transpol in Auer.
The psychologist met Camille Auer twice and, on the basis of these, wrote a report that should be defined in order to obtain Auer’s right to care and help.
The subject's sense of reality is exposed to destabilization.
The subject’s perception of the self appears to be fragmented at the border state level, and the unstable characteristics of the personality are highlighted.
Auer did not recognize himself from these descriptions.
It was a shock to hear that I was diagnosed with mental illness," Auer says.
There was even greater shock when Auer was not given sex reassignment treatment.
According to the medical staff, his resources were not sufficient to start the process.
He was denied his own identity.
Then, on February 11, 2015, Auer walked out of the meeting and kicked the television in the waiting area of the Transpol.
Later that television was the birthplace of a work called Monument for the Excluded, in which Auer reflected on his experience of power and its use.
It’s crazy that any person who is defined as a woman at birth can enlarge their breasts, but a diagnosis is needed to remove breasts,” Auer says.
Your body is not yours if you feel that you are anything other than the amount of your gender defined at birth.
Unfortunately, Auer’s experience is not the only one of its kind.
The process of sex correction is more severe for many mental reasons than purely for medical purposes.
Those who go through it will meet dozens of people who need to be justified by their own existence and their right to their own sex experience.
It’s crazy that people who are in need of support and assistance are denied treatment, claiming that their resources are not enough,” Auer says.
Many of the people who have applied for the process have mental symptoms behind them: depression, anxiety, possible bullying experiences.
On this basis, medical personnel may order that treatment cannot be started.
Preventing access to treatment and help can put a person in an even worse situation than it was before the start of the process,” Auer says.
Auer’s personal exhibition also deals with anxiety and thoughts about suicide.
In the text of the exhibition, Auer writes: "I have had suicidal thoughts throughout my adult life and that's what people tend to find difficult to digest."
Depression has been treated with drugs and when Auer started using hormones, he felt relieved.
He had finally been able to say the sensations that had already existed in childhood and teenage years.
Why the wide jaw didn't seem to fit into your body and why the chest muscles had to be round instead of a flat chest.
The most important thing for Auer is that there are people near him who see him.
Being seen is a basic need.
You have to justify yourself so much by talking, dressing, using sound and moving,” he says.
Today Auer feels already seen, she exists as a woman.
However, at the beginning of the process, random comments from loved ones could have hurt a lot.
It hurts the most when people close to you are misrepresented.
They should know and know who I am, but they will not or will not be able to internalize it,” he continues.
However, not all trans people need physical changes.
They do not suffer from body dysphoria, or body conflict, where the body or parts of it can cause anxiety and even physical pain.
However, without the use of hormones and a long research process, official confirmation of sex cannot be obtained.
There is no medical basis for these studies," Auer says.
And that is true.
For example, in Denmark, in June 2014, Parliament adopted a new procedure for the recognition of legal sex.
The new legislation is based on the right to self-determination with regard to the legal sex.
An adult applicant submits a written application for a new personal identity code, stating that he/she feels that he/she is of another gender.
After a six-month cooling-off period, the applicant confirms his/her application in writing and the Ministry gives the applicant a new personal identity code.
This right to self-determination is also required in Finland, and this requirement is also reflected in Auer’s exhibition.
It has not been a therapeutic experience for the artist, but it is a political and artistic collection.
I want to believe that art still has weight and that it can bring about political changes at a time when politicians have forgotten about human rights.
