Civil Rights Organization issued a travel warning to Missouri
The NAACP National Agency for African-American Civil Rights has issued a travel warning for Missouri due to discriminatory state practices and racist attacks there.
The NAACP travel bulletin for Missouri will enter into force on 28 August 2017 and calls on African-American tourists, visitors and locals to pay special attention and to exercise extreme caution when travelling in a state where a number of questionable racial events have recently taken place," the agency said.
In addition, the implementation of state laws is disproportionately targeted at minorities. According to the NAACP, these factors led to the issuing of a travel warning.
People's civil rights are violated.
They are stopped by skin color and beaten or killed,” said Rod Chapel, President of NAACP Missouri, to Kansas City Star.
We have not heard one in so many cases before in such a short time.”
The Missouri travel bulletin is the first warning for the United States of America.
The organisation cited racist comments against African-American students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a 28-year-old black from Tennessee.
Sanders died under questionable circumstances earlier this year. He was driving through the state when his car ran out of fuel. The Missouri police arrested him even though he was not charged with a crime.
The travel bulletin also referred to a statement by the Missouri Attorney General that police are 75% more likely to stop a black driver than white.
The purpose of the travel bulletin is to encourage people to be alert and warn their families, friends and colleagues about what can happen in Missouri,” Chapel says.
People need to prepare, for example, by taking money with them to pay guarantees, or by telling relatives that they are going to travel through the state.”
According to the FBI, one hundred hate crimes were recorded in Missouri in 2015, the sixteenth largest state in the United States.
The travel warning is also a response to the new Missouri law, which makes it difficult to sue companies for discrimination in housing and employment relationships.
The Constitutional Civil Rights Organization (ACLU) recently issued travel warnings to Texas and Arizona after they had passed immigration laws obliging the police to arrest people for immigration violations, which, according to the organization, increases racial profiling.
Travel warnings are usually published by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and apply to other states, but recently they have been published by NGOs in response to certain laws and developments in the United States.
