Hogan spokesperson, Amelia Chasse, defended the governor's actions in an interview with the Washington Post.
However, labeling commentators as trolls, spammers or haters is too easy.
Washington Post interviewed users blocked by Hogan on Facebook.
They turned out to be ordinary people who wanted to talk to their chosen leaders, not trolls, but teachers, entrepreneurs, pastors, etc.
They said that their comments were respectful, thoughtful and relevant.
In his comment, the pastor quoted the Bible; he wanted to appeal to the Catholic faith in Hogan.
Lawyer Lakshmi Sarma Ramani of the Maryland Bowie was not hostile but asked a question about hate crimes.
I am politely disappointed that Hogan had not taken a stand on hate crimes and other recent news,” he wrote in the Washington Post’s comments.
I also find it unacceptable that when more people comment on the same thing, they are immediately regarded as an organized group and ignored as a large group of concerned citizens.
The governor’s staff called the comments a “central attack”; someone else could call them a promotion of what was considered important.
In a Facebook era, communication is easy to manage by blocking a reviewer or deleting a critical comment.
In the old days, staff should have been sent to collect and burn newspapers with critical editorials, or to arrest and silence protesters.
But it really is the same thing, now only digitally.
