Poverty and death in Indonesia's Gold Country
Bardina Degei does not use stoves in cooking.
He also rarely uses the pot.
Degei lives in a wooden building in Enarotal, the capital of the Paniai region, located in the restless province of Papua, Indonesia. When he cooks dinner, he usually puts sweet potatoes – locally “nota” – directly into the fireplace.
After half an hour, the burnt sweet potato is eaten greedily with bare, unwashed hands.
Degei has no furniture in his home. He sits on a muddy ground floor, where he usually also takes care of his daily chores, such as laundry in the cloudy water from the nearby swamp.
The office of the toilet is supplied by a bucket in a roofless room.
Degei is the youngest of her husband's four wives and has not been assigned fields to care for her.
Polygamy is common here.
Late work can be dangerous: most men in the village are unemployed, and many drink a lot, and soldiers must also be taken into account.
Nobody dares to walk in the village after five in the evening,” Degei says.
This is a rare glimpse of everyday life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony annexed to Indonesia in 1969. The annexation was preceded by a controversial referendum in which 1 026 village elders were forced to vote in public in front of the occupying forces.
The Dutch local independence movement quickly turned its anger on the Jakarta government, which strictly controls the region and prevents foreign journalists and human rights observers from accessing it.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, and the eastern part of the island belongs to Papua New Guinea.
Enarotali is remote and sluggish. The journey starts with a one and a half hour flight from the provincial capital of Jayapura to Nabire and continues with a stomach-wringing five hour drive by rental car.
There is no public transport here.
Around 19 000 people in the city have wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, the corrugated roofs of which have been stained with yellowish-brown rust.
Few Indonesians have come here, not to mention journalists and foreigners.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, the Papuan Mee Pago tribe worshipped the god Uga Tamee.
Other changes have also taken place.
We didn’t have such clothes,” Degei says. He means his colourful, hand-woven wrap-around headdress, dark skirt and bright-colored blouse.
In the past, we only had leaves as a blanket for our bodies.
Papua is the poorest province of Indonesia, with 28% of its inhabitants living below the poverty line, and child mortality and illiteracy are among the highest in Asia.
But it is also a golden land of Indonesia.
Paniai is about the size of New Jersey with 153 000 inhabitants. Only about a hundred kilometres from Paniai is Grasberg, the world’s largest and most profitable gold mine. It is owned by Freeport McMoran, a company based in Phoenix, USA.
In 2015, the mine provided Freeport with $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua has an estimated $78 billion in wood reserves.
However, for the Papuans, these wealth brings misery, as it means a suffocating presence of a strong Indonesian army.
In 2005, the New York Times revealed that Freeport paid nearly $20 million to local military personnel and military local units between 1998 and 2004, with individual officers paid up to $150 000.
Papua's demands for greater autonomy threaten this source of income and are mercilessly silenced.
According to human rights activists, since 1969, the Indonesian army has killed more than 500 000 Papuans and raped, tortured and imprisoned thousands.
According to the Asian Commission on Human Rights, mass murders in the highlands of the Papuan tribes in the 1970s took place in proportion to the proportions of genocide.
Last year, the Indonesian police arrested more than 3 900 people in the area during peaceful protests.
In the 2016 report of the Archdiocese of Brisbane, We Will Lose Everything, there are reports of the atrocities of the previous year, such as executions without trial, torture – rapes and electric shocks are particularly popular – and relentless attacks towards peaceful demonstrations.
It is difficult to calculate the number of victims because there are weekly cases,” says Andreas Harsono, Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
The screw has been tightened as the natural resources of Papua attract migrants from other parts of Indonesia.
Of the 3.5 million inhabitants of the province, 83% are Christians, but the demographics are changing as Indonesia's populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi move into the region in the hope of a better livelihood for Muslims.
Warung food stalls in Java sell fried chicken and gado-gado vegetable mix in peanut sauce.
It is difficult for locals to compete.
Migrants have started selling chicken and vegetables in the marketplace cheaper than locals,” says 24-year-old Abeth You, who came from Pania and moved to the provincial capital after work.
Local women lost their customers.
Indonesian President Jo Widodo – nicknamed Jokowi – promised in his 2014 election campaign to address the injustices and human rights violations in Papua.
Papua consists of 29 districts, and this former carpenter won a vote in 27 districts, including Pania, on his way to Jakarta Presidential Palace.
But little has changed in Papua, and the locals feel deceived.
Our hearts were broken because we voted for Joow in 2014 and we expected him to fulfill our wishes and restore justice,” You says.
Panias experienced some kind of wave base only two months after the official inauguration of Jowi in October.
