The latest results of the medical age tests for asylum seekers in Sweden have been published. The results of the new assessment method reveal that more than 80 per cent of those tested were estimated to be over the age of 18. However, not everyone considers the tests reliable.
The Swedish National Forensic Medicine Agency started testing earlier this year.
The new test was introduced after the Swedish Immigration Service was criticised for failing to determine the actual age of applicants claiming to be minors.
The Finnish Immigration Service has carried out 6 880 tests so far, and the National Board of Forensic Medicine has now published the results of 2 481 tests, which were carried out between mid-March and the end of July 2017.
Eighty per cent of those tested, i.e. in 2002 the asylum seeker was said to be over 18 years of age. In addition, in 25 cases, the forensics agency determined that the test was “possibly 18 years of age or older”.
In 432 cases, it was concluded that the asylum seeker was “possibly under 18 years of age”.
The tests were only carried out in cases where there were grounds to suspect the age indicated by the applicant.
According to Johan Göransson, the results are consistent with the results of previous months.
The figures are fairly consistent. There are no major differences in the statistics for the previous months,” he told The Local.
Although a large number of applicants were said to be over the age of 18, this does not necessarily mean that they were lying about their age.
In May, the Agency published the results of 581 tests and reported that in 442 cases there were “references that the study was 18 years old or older”.
When Svenska Dagbladet examined the same results, it turned out that in 243 cases the applicant had openly stated that he would be 18 years old this year.
The medical age assessment method used in the tests takes X-rays of wisdom teeth and magnetic images of knee joints. Then dentists and radiologists analyze the images. The method has also been criticized.
One of the suspects is the endocrinologist Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institute, whose work involves assessing the biological maturity of people.
I have had reason to think about it, and I think the method used is not the right one.
Determination of biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we are not able to determine the age, we should not pretend that we are capable of doing so,” he said to the Metro newspaper.
However, Göransson of the Finnish Institute of Forensic Medicine defended the accuracy of the tests: “In general, one can say that the risk of determining a child as an adult is small.
