The police just killed an 18-year-old boy, and his body is still on the street.
Confused, he noted that no one else had posted the same information to his feed, which is why he closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
His timeline had numerous retweets from @TheePharaoh.
The user name belongs to a rapper in St. Louis who tweeted in real time about Michael Brown's death. The white police had shot an unarmed 18-year-old Blackman in Ferguson, Missouri.
The user had also posted a picture of Brown's lifeless body on the street, where it was left for four hours.
This is incredible,” Ferrell thought.
But death was nothing new to him and his community.
When he returned to Twitter later that evening, people were told that they were accumulating on Canfield Drive.
Users posted pictures of police locks and shouting people, as well as a man who claimed to be Brown’s father, whose sign read: “Ferguson police just killed my unarmed son!”
Ferrell followed a real-time video of the police standing in front of the protesters with a barking dog.
He also says he saw a video in which another police officer tuned his rifle and shouted, "I'll kill all of you... the animals."
This is not normal,” Ferrell remembers.
It was not the kind of murder that we are already used to and that could be said to be typical.
Then I felt cold colors.
I was angry and crying.”
He booked a return flight home the next day.
The plane landed at eleven o'clock in the evening. Ferrell went to pick up his six-year-old daughter from his father and decided that they would go to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson in the next almost three years has been made in the documentary Whose Streets, which premiered in cinemas on 11 August 2017.
The film is a story of survival and demonstration, love and loss, and strength and perseverance from the point of view of the local people who set out on the streets to demand answers.
When Ferrell drove towards Ferguson with their daughter in a flower dress and a crown that was compatible with it, they had another conversation about “what it’s like to live in black and under what circumstances.” They had talked about it countless times before that morning.
Do you remember when I told you how the blacks had to fight for what they believe?” Ferrell remembers saying to her daughter.
We’re going to Ferguson because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and that’s not right.”
I couldn’t help but take my daughter with me,” Ferrell said later.
Today’s events are the culmination of the past.
My daughter has the right to know it and grow up to it.
He must have the capacity for activism and organization, but he must also know the different layers and circumstances of living as a black person, and he must know what we must do to liberate ourselves.
Fortunately, although I have been able to protect her from blatant racism, she is still like other black girls.
I feel that I would harm him if I protected him from reality.”
Their first stop in Ferguson was South Florissant Road, opposite the police station, which became a camp for activists who were waiting for information about the case and eventually learned that no charges would be brought against the police.
From there, Ferrell and his daughter went to help a local entrepreneur who made lunch packages.
They packed lunches in bags and distributed them to the protesters.
Ferrell gradually began to take a new approach to activism.
My activism changed completely after August 9," he says. While studying at the University of Missouri in St. Louis, Ferrell was the chair of a minority student organization, where he focused on food law and health inequalities in black communities.
I had no experience in organizing.
Somehow it just happened.”
A few weeks later, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, an assistant director of the document.
Folayan said that he and photographer Lucas Alvarado-Farrar “wanted to tell” what was going on.
He asked Ferrell, “Do you really want to tell what is happening, or do you want a story that you can use?”
The reason for this suspicion was the innumerable appearance of people in the local community, usually whites, who only wanted to benefit from its difficulties and perseverance.
We had heard that those born and raised in Ferguson had no common voice,” Folayan recently said in an interview. “We wanted to do things differently.”
Folayan had already contacted co-director Damon Davis, who is known for his activism with prisoners sentenced to death.
Davis' involvement led Ferrell to join the project along with six other locals. The crew followed the events in the years following the Brown shooting.
This is not a document in which someone speaks to us or speaks on our behalf, but we speak,” Davis says.
For me, the most important thing was how local people were portrayed in the film, because I was portrayed in the same way.
According to Folayan, the aim was not to focus on Ferrell's experiences, because it was to show that the popular movement "is not about a charismatic leader, but about a community". However, Ferrell proved to be the most open of the depictions.
That’s why the documentary shows surprisingly private aspects of Ferrell’s life, such as falling in love and getting married.
I felt pretty naked,” Ferrell laughs, telling me what it felt like to see a movie for the first time.
But I understood that this work and the human portrayal of blacks require a certain vulnerability.
In addition, Ferrell’s story times and brings back to centre the role of black queer women in the wider Black Lives Matter movement.
The movement was created on social media (#BlackLivesMatter) after police shot black teenage boy Trayvon Martin in 2012. Two of the three founders of the movement identify with queer identity.
The leadership of black queer women has kept the whole movement going,” says Ferrell. “It’s because we have to fight on many fronts all the time.
Black queer women have had to endure everything.”
Folayan agrees: “The movement is indeed maintained by black women, among whom there are a lot of queer women.”
He stresses, however, that Ferrell was not “intentionally” selected for the document because of his queer identity.
He got the energy going,” Folayan says.
It is no coincidence, however, that she was at the forefront. Black queer women live at the cutting point of many things, and they have a lot at stake.
His energy is transmitted from the big screen.”
The news crews have left Ferguson a long time ago, but the relationship between the community and the police is still tense.
Ferrell still has two and a half years left on parole, and was convicted of blocking the motorway during the demonstration.
His description of the social political atmosphere in his home corners is short and concise: “A mess.”
Yet he still relies on the slogan he learned from the outside on the streets of Ferguson three years ago:
It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We must love and support each other.
