Red meat, dairy products and chocolate may relieve irritable bowel syndrome
Red meat and chocolate may sound like nightmares in the digestive system.
However, a recent study suggests the opposite: a diet rich in meat protein and dairy products may facilitate irritable bowel syndrome.
Irritable bowel syndrome is an incurable disease that affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300 000 people in the United Kingdom. It causes stomach cramps, swelling, recurrent or bloody diarrhoea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
People with irritable bowel syndrome are usually advised to avoid meat and dairy products. However, researchers at the University of Washington found that the essential amino acid in protein, tryptophan, helps the body develop immune cells that strengthen intestinal tolerance.
According to Marco Colonna, the leader of the study, immune cells guard the gut and ensure that harmful microbes that hide in the food do not enter the body.
The cells that cause inflammation balance the cells that strengthen tolerance. They protect the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance falls too close to the inflammation, then the result may be irritable bowel syndrome.
The studies found that immune cells that strengthen tolerance are present in mice with a specific bacteria in their intestines.
This bacteria needs tryptophan in order for immune cells to start to appear. Tryptophan is one of the building blocks of proteins.
We found a link between the development of Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria and the development of tolerance cells. Lactobacillus reuteri is part of the normal microbiome of the gut,” explains Professor Colonna.
The more tryptophan was present in the mouse diet, the more such immune cells were present.
If the same works in humans, a combination of Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria and a diet rich in tryptophan can strengthen intestinal tolerance and reduce inflammation sensitivity.
When studying immune cells that strengthen tolerance, Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barragan found that although one group of mice had such cells, they were not found in mice of the same species that were kept separate from the other group.
He suspected that the difference was related to microbiomes in the intestines of mice, i.e. the normal community of bacteria, fungi and viruses in the digestive tract.
When the gut DNA of mice was studied, six bacterial species were found in mice with immune cells, but not in other mice.
When Lactobacillus reuteri was administered to mice in a sterile environment who did not have intestinal microbiome and did not develop immune cells, immune cells began to appear.
The researchers wanted to find out how bacteria affect the immune system. They raised Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in the liquid and transferred small amounts of fluid – without bacteria – from mice to immature immune cells.
The immune cells evolved into cells that strengthen tolerance.
When the active ingredient was purified from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of the metabolism of tryptophan, known as indole-3 lactic acid.
When scientists doubled the amount of tryptophan in mice’ nutrition, the number of tolerable cells increased by about 50 percent. When tryptophan was halved, the number of cells decreased by half from the previous one.
According to Cervantes-Barrangan, humans have the same tolerability-enhancing cells as the mouse, and most of us have Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in our digestive tract.
It is not yet known whether Tryptophan by-products from Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria can develop in humans in the same way as in mice. However, Tryptophan-associated genetic defects have been observed in patients with irritable bowel syndrome.
We probably want to promote the development of such cells because they regulate inflammation on the inner surface of the intestines,” says Cervantes-Barragan.
A high level of tryptophan combined with Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria may contribute to their proliferation.
