NOW: Trump-sanctioned calls were invented - White House spokesman: "I wouldn't say it was a lie"
The White House admits that the two calls mentioned by US President Donald Trump never took place, according to the New York Times.
Trump's calls with both the President of Mexico and the leader of the scouting organization have proven to be invented.
White House spokesman Sarah Huckabee Sanders confirmed that no calls had taken place.
He said, however, that Trump did not lie.
According to Sanders, many of the leaders of the scouts spoke to Trump personally, and with Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto, Trump had spoken at the G20 in Hamburg.
I wouldn't say it was a lie, it's a pretty tough accusation.
Those conversations took place, not just on the phone, but face-to-face,” Sanders explained.
Speech to the scouts provoked disapproval
Trump said on Monday that the Mexican president called him and praised Trump for successfully eradicating illegal immigration.
According to Trump, Pena Nieto said that few people will ever cross the southern border of Mexico because they know that the journey will in any case fill the U.S. border.
On Wednesday, the Mexican government issued a statement saying that there was no such call.
On Tuesday, Politico released a full version of Trump's interview with The Wall Street Journal.
In it, Trump spoke at a major meeting of a national patrol organization in West Virginia.
I got a call from the head of the patrol boys, he said it was the coolest speech ever made to them.
They were very grateful,” Trump said.
On Wednesday, a patrol organization announced that it was not aware of any of its leaders' calls to Trump.
According to the press release, the former statement by the leader of the organization, Michael Surbaugh, in which he had asked for Trump’s speech to be forgiven by the patrols, speaks for himself.
Trump's speech at the meeting of the scouting organisation was a source of great surprise, as it was exceptionally political in relation to the nature of the event.
Among other things, he praised the results of last autumn’s presidential elections.
